<TEXT>
imagine a 20watt 
refrigerator light bulb burning in the dark 275 billion miles away 
now imagine the sophisticated eyes needed to see the light 
voyager 2 heading for neptune is emitting 20 watts of radio 
signals information coded in binary bits ones and zeros on the 
space probes health and from its scientific instruments and cameras 
think of that lightbulb as flickering and that flickering 
contains the information that voyager is sending back to us said 
bill brundage voyager preparation manager for the very large array 
radio telescope 
the signals have become fainter since voyagers encounters with 
jupiter in 1979 saturn in 1981 and uranus in 1986 the signals and 
commands sent to the 12yearold probe take four hours and six 
minutes to cross 275 billion miles at the speed of light larger 
antennas and more sensitive receivers are needed on earth to receive 
the signals and more power is needed to transmit commands to the 
craft which will pass fly within 3000 miles of neptune on aug 24 
the national aeronautics and space administrations deep space 
network is used to talk to voyager the dsn has three complexes 
goldstone in californias mojave desert madrid spain and 
tidbinbilla australia near canberra 
when voyager flew by uranus the california and australian 
listening posts used three antenna dishes each one 210 feet across 
and two 112 feet and the madrid station used one of each said 
mary beth murrill a spokeswoman for the nasa jet propulsion 
laboratory in pasadena calif the canberra complex also was linked 
to australias 210foot parkes radio astronomy telescope 
for neptune the 210foot dishes at goldstone canberra and 
madrid have been increased to 230 feet and another 112foot antenna 
was built at madrid in addition the vla is being used in 
conjunction with goldstone parkes again is linked with canberra 
and a japanese telescope will be added to the network 
the different sites ensure that at least one station can 
communicate with the spacecraft despite the earths rotation 
brundage said 
the vla alone gives us almost a third more images than if we 
didnt have it said norm haynes voyager project manager at jpl 
the vla is a oneofakind spaceage erector set sitting on an 
ancient lake bed the site is skirted by four mountain ranges 
protecting it from much of the electronic interference from 
television radios aircraft and the like 
it consists of 27 white dishshaped antennas each 82 feet in 
diameter 92 feet high and weighing 235 tons the dishes sit on the 
plains of san augustin amid tumbleweed cattle and sparse vegetation 
at an altitude of 7000 feet 
the dishes are arranged along three arms of railroad track laid 
out in the shape of a y two arms are 13 miles long and the third is 
118 miles the earth rotates the y like a turntable creating 
images that have the same detail as if using a radio telescope up to 
26 miles in diameter 
a special 36wheel transporter moves each antenna to one of 72 
observation stations along the three arms this acts like a zoom 
lens the farther out the dishes the higher the resolution the 
closer in the larger the field of view 
nasa spent 65 million to equip each dish to receive voyagers 
signals it also set up special techniques and installed two big 
diesel generators to guard against lightningcaused power 
fluctuations during the thunderstorm season 
the separation of the listening posts around the world just 
like the separation of the vla dishes strengthen the sensitivity 
of the network the signal vla gets from voyager is sent via 
satellite to goldstone where the two signals are combined decoded 
and sent via microwave to jpl in pasadena 
</TEXT>
