a bomb exploded early sunday at a 
crowded exhibition attended by president ranasinghe premadasa and 
senior members of his cabinet but they escaped injury police said 
however at least one person was killed and 30 were wounded they 
said 
no one claimed responsibility for the blast which occurred 
shortly after midnight at a governmentsponsored exhibition in 
mahiyangana 70 miles northeast of colombo 
but police blamed members of the peoples liberation front a 
leftwing ethnic sinhalese group trying to overthrow the 
sinhalesedominated government 
also sunday security forces in the south arrested 3237 
sinhalese youths suspected of belonging to the front according to a 
police official in colombo 
it was the largest such crackdown against the group in nearly two 
years said the officer who cannot be identified under briefing 
rules 
the front has been blamed for more than 3500 killings since july 
1987 when indian peacekeeping forces arrived on this indian ocean 
island to enforce a peace accord between the government and the 
tamil minority 
the front contends the accord grants too many concessions to the 
tamils and the indian soldiers threaten sri lankan sovereignty 
front members have vowed to kill anyone who supports the pact 
last month premadasa asked india to pull out its troops by the 
end of july india refused saying a quick withdrawal could stir 
even more ethnic violence 
india sent troops to sri lanka under a peace accord signed by 
indian prime minister rajiv gandhi and premadasas predecessor 
junius r jayewardene the accord proposed to give tamils limited 
autonomy in exchange for surrendering their weapons but militant 
tamils rejected it 
tamils who comprise 18 percent of sri lankas 16 million people 
contend they suffer job and educational discrimination sinhalese 
make up 75 percent of the population 
